3️⃣ Visual states & evolution rules
Make the planets change over time, but all from data.

Focus state (NOW / NEXT / RESTING)
NOW

High glowIntensity

Closer orbitRadius

Faster spinSpeed

Slight camera parallax towards them when you enter the scene

NEXT

Medium glow

Mid orbit

Normal spin

RESTING

Low glow

Large orbit radius

Slower spin, darker rim-light to keep them visible but calm

You already compute NOW/NEXT/RESTING from pushed_at and pins in the Hub; feed that directly to the 3D scene.

Activity & health
Heavy open issues, few closes →

High stormIntensity (moving clouds, lightning flashes)

Higher lavaActivity (glowing fissures)

Recent issue closes →

Storms calm, lava recedes, surface roughness decreases

近期 release →

Temporary increased haloPulse + a ring of fireworks/comets for 24–48h

Social & structure
Stars → radius + glow (log scale so “big repo” doesn’t explode)

Forks → 1–5 moons (clamped)

Watchers/stargazers growth → slow breathing pulse in atmosphere

Quests
Each quest (unchecked item) → small light beacon on night side of planet

Hover / focus a planet → quest markers brighten, showing “this world has missions.”

No quests → visible but low-contrast surface; card copy “No quest signal yet” stays the same, just visually reflected.

4️⃣ Hyper-modern 3D UI layout
Your reference images are dense; your UI should be cleaner, more like modern 3D data viz (think Globe.GL style minimal overlays, not game HUD noise).

Main layout
Left/center: React Three Fiber <Canvas> with:

Free-orbit camera (mouse drag / scroll zoom)

Soft space background (starfield, but tinted to your brand)

Planets positioned on concentric shells:

inner shell = NOW

mid shell = NEXT

outer shell = RESTING

Right-hand panel: Your existing PlanetSheet UI:

Repo name + lore name

Stats (stars, forks, issues, activity timeline)

Quests as list with “Open repo” / “Start quest”

Accessibility controls (motion/contrast toggle)

React Three Fiber is designed for declarative scenes in React and works well with Tailwind or plain CSS overlay for clean 2D panels.

Interaction model
Click / Enter on a planet:

Planet scales slightly (data-driven scale)

Camera eases in to follow it (orbit focus)

Right panel opens with PlanetSheet

Hover:

Highlight ring; tooltips are optional because the right panel gives detail

Search/filter:

Search box filters both 2D list and 3D scene (non-matching planets fade out)

Focus filter buttons (NOW/NEXT/RESTING) reshape the scene (only those shells visible)

This mirrors best-practice 3D UIs: 3D for spatial overview, 2D for detail.

5️⃣ Accessibility & motion controls (hyper but kind)
You already care about this; keep it front and centre.

Respect prefers-reduced-motion:

If reduce, disable orbit motion, storms, camera auto-move, and any “breathing” loops; keep only essential transitions.

Keyboard:

Tab focus cycles through planets in a deterministic order (NOW first)

Enter/Space selects planet, opens sheet; Escape closes sheet and returns focus

Text:

HUD text and panel content use your existing 2D layer; 3D scene never hides readable info behind camera motion.

Hyper UI ≠ spinning everything all the time; it’s calm depth with bursts of motion only when needed.

6️⃣ Visual style: “Hyper” but clean
Pick a direction that feels modern and ND-friendly, not noisy:

Color:

Dark space background

One accent colour family per biome (so similar worlds feel grouped)

Keep HUD/UI in beige/neutral Nexus palette you already use for the Hub, with teal accent only for primary actions.

Lighting:

Soft key light + rim light around each planet

No harsh bloom or lens flare that would make reading exhausting

Composition:

Center cluster of NOW planets

NEXT ring around them

RESTING worlds scattered further out, slightly blurred/dim

Use Globe.GL and other modern 3D data-viz examples as references: they show how to keep text legible and motion restrained while still feeling futuristic.

7️⃣ How to build it (high-level steps)
Add a planetVisual builder

Input: your existing repo + lore + quest data

Output: PlanetVisual fields as above

Create <PlanetMesh /> in React Three Fiber

Takes PlanetVisual and renders sphere, rings, moons, storms, beacons

Uses useFrame for spin/orbit animation, but gates it on motion prefs.

Create <UniverseScene />

Maps over all planets, positions them by focus state

Handles camera controls + hover/click interaction

Wire to Hub

Share state with your 2D page: same filters, same search, same PlanetSheet

Add a “Universe View” toggle button at the top of the Hub

